<TITLE> Blue-chips drive DSE </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 15 (bdnews24.com)Stocks rallied Sunday as prices of blue-chips surged due to a sharp increase in demand for the shares of banks, insurance and non-bank financial institutions. Mutual funds and IT stocks gave extra pace to the market. But cement shares declined amid profit-taking while power and pharmaceuticals stocks finished mixed. "It reflects high demand for quality shares in a situation where banks and non-bank financial institutions maintain surplus funds," said chief executive of DSE Salahuddin Ahmed, referring to about Tk 10,000 crore in surplus funds held by banks and NBFIs. The DGEN or general index on the Dhaka Stock Exchange rallied 25.26 points or 1.14 percent to 2229.38. The DSI or all-share price index gained 22.91 points or 1.26 percent to close at 1830.23. The DSE-20 blue chip index surged 47.57 points or 2.53 percent to 1927.14. Turnover however fell to Tk 1.65 billion from Thursday's Tk 1.69 billion. Of the issues traded, 116 issued finished higher, 76 lost and 22 held steady. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished higher although turnover dropped to Tk 232.60 million from Thursday's Tk 263.21 million. Gainers outnumbered losers 66 to 35. A total of eight issues remained unchanged on the CSE. On the DSE, top issue in turnover at Tk 121.12 million, Summit Power increased 3.39 percent to Tk 1058.75 following reports that it will soon build two new power plants with generation capacities of 33 MW and 11 MW. Summit will borrow from local and multinational banks and NBFIs to meet 80 percent of the project cost. The remaining cost will be undertaken from its own equity, it said. BRAC Bank, second leader in turnover, slipped 0.06 percent to Tk 790.25 due to profit taking. DESCO, Power Grid Company of Bangladesh and Grameen1 mutual fund followed BRAC Bank on the turnover table. DESCO gained 2.72 percent to close at Tk 997.25 but a selloff pushed Power Grid to end 0.46 percent lower at Tk 589. Grameen1 MF also fell 0.18 percent to Tk 54.10. Meghna Life Insurance, Aziz Pipes and Singer Bangladesh were the main gainers. Major losers were Alamin Chemicals, BD Online and Niloy Cement. bdn
